    "slug": "tirzepatide-cv-label",
    "url": "/news/tirzepatide-cv-label.html",
    "title": "FDA expands tirzepatide label to include cardiovascular event reduction",
    "lede": "The FDA has expanded the tirzepatide label to include reduction of major adverse cardiovascular events in adults with obesity or overweight plus established cardiovascular disease. Why this matters more than it sounds Until now, prescribing tirzepatide for weight management or pre-diabetes was a coverage fight. Insuran",
    "html": "<p>The FDA has expanded the tirzepatide label to include reduction of major adverse cardiovascular events in adults with obesity or overweight plus established cardiovascular disease.</p>\n<h2>Why this matters more than it sounds</h2>\n<p>Until now, prescribing tirzepatide for weight management or pre-diabetes was a coverage fight. Insurance plans routinely declined coverage on the grounds that it was \"lifestyle\" rather than treating cardiovascular risk. With a formal cardiovascular indication, that argument gets harder to sustain.</p>\n<p>This is a near-replay of what happened with semaglutide after the SELECT trial: a quiet shift in insurance posture, broader access, and downward price pressure on cash pay over the following 12–18 months.</p>\n<h2>What it means for the <a href=\"/items/glp1-agonists.html\">glp1-agonists</a> tier rating</h2>\n<p>We don't move tier ratings on label expansions alone. The underlying evidence — SURMOUNT-MMO — is the actual update. The trial showed:</p>\n<ul><li><strong>Primary endpoint</strong> (composite MACE): hazard ratio 0.78, 95% CI 0.69–0.88</li><li><strong>Cardiovascular death:</strong> roughly 18% reduction</li><li><strong>Heart failure hospitalization:</strong> the strongest single signal at ~24% reduction</li><li><strong>Adverse events:</strong> consistent with prior trials — mostly GI, mostly tolerable, mostly self-resolving</li></ul>\n<p>This puts tirzepatide on roughly the same evidence footing as semaglutide for cardiovascular protection in the overweight/obese population. The relevant clinical decision is no longer \"does this work\" — it's \"which agent, what dose, and when do I start.\"</p>\n<h2>What it doesn't change</h2>\n<ul><li>It's still not approved or evidence-supported for normal-weight adults seeking longevity benefits.</li><li>It's still expensive at cash prices, though the trajectory is downward.</li><li>It still requires a long-term commitment — discontinuation rapidly returns weight and metabolic markers to baseline.</li><li>It still doesn't fix sleep, exercise, or diet quality. Adding a GLP-1 to a <a href=\"/items/sleep-architecture.html\">sleep-architecture</a> deficit and zero training is leaving most of the longevity benefit on the table.</li></ul>\n<h2>Practical guidance for readers</h2>\n<p>If you're already taking the wizard's \"discuss with your doctor about a GLP-1\" advice, this week's news strengthens that advice. If you're looking for a longevity drug because you read about rapamycin somewhere — a GLP-1 has more human cardiovascular mortality evidence than every Frontier-tier intervention on this site combined.</p>\n<p>That doesn't make it the right drug for you. But it does make it the conversation worth having.</p>",
    "date": "2026-05-03",
    "tag": "glp1",
    "tags": [
      "glp1",
      "tirzepatide",
      "cardiovascular",
      "fda"
    ]
